#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:8
msgid "SYNOPSIS: Encrypting swap partition"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:13
msgid ""
"DESCRIPTION: Here is a way to enable disk encryption on HLFS system. Aim is "
"to provide native swap encryption and possibility to encrypt the root "
"partition later, with third-part software."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:19
msgid ""
"ATTACHMENTS: * ftp://ngc891.blogdns.net/pub/hlfs/hlfs-607-eswap-1.patch * "
"http://www.linuxfromscratch.org/patches/downloads/util-linux/util-linux-2.12r-loop_AES-3.1b.patch "
"* "
"http://www.linuxfromscratch.org/patches/downloads/linux/linux-2.6.14.3-loop_AES-3.1b.patch "
"* "
"http://www.linuxfromscratch.org/patches/downloads/gnupg/gnupg-1.4.2-loop_AES-3.1b.patch"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:23
msgid ""
"PREREQUISITES: This hint is written for HLFS but can be easily applied to "
"LFS. You should have some basic knowledge about devices and using swap."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:25
msgid "HINT:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:27
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"I. About encrypting disk\n"
"------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:32
msgid ""
"A Linux system already provides some basic security environment including "
"users and groups, passwords, permissions, and n ow access control via "
"SELinux project."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:36
msgid ""
"However, this could be not enough in some cases like attackers with physical "
"access. If someone can physically access your hard drive and mount it in an "
"other computer, he overpasses the system and can read whatever he wants."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:42
msgid ""
"The problem is the same with the swap partition. It stores short lifetime "
"data including most of the things you have just done with the computer and "
"that didn't fit in the RAM. The system continously overwrite this partition "
"and there is no easy structure inside but an attacker could seek in for "
"passwords and other data you just typed."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:50
msgid ""
"One protection against this kind of attack is swap encryption. It means "
"cipher your data with an algorithm, so you need a passphrase and/or a key to "
"access clearly to it. Even, some ciphers like AES provide you \"plausible "
"deniability\".  It means there is no way to know that the partition is "
"actually encrypted because it looks just like trash, like an empty "
"partition. So, there is no more problem for the syst em being overpassed by "
"physical access."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:52
msgid "Encrypting your partitions could increase drastically your data security."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:54
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"II. How to do?\n"
"--------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:58
msgid ""
"There is several ways to encrypt disk on Linux, including cryptoloop, "
"dm-crypt, loop-AES and StegFS."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:61
msgid ""
"StegFS is a special encrypted file system. It's sounds really great but is "
"still under development and needs big modifications of the base system."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:67
msgid ""
"Cryptoloop was a special loop device included in the kernel that provides "
"access to encrypted device by loopback. Everybody was happy to have such an "
"easy way to access encrypted device, but unfortunately, it was found that "
"cryptoloop has a flaw and cannot be trust. If you can find cryptoloop in "
"some linux distribution, it was actually removed from the official Linux "
"kernel source code [1]."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:74
msgid ""
"dm-crypt is an encrypted device mapper created to replace cryptoloop "
"[2]. You can find it in the official source, under the device mapper "
"sub-section. It is supposed to avoid the flaw of cryptoloop, but actually, "
"it fails. You ca n find on the web more informations about that [3]. So even "
"if it's available natively in the kernel it should be avoid for more "
"security."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:78
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"*UPDATE* It seems that dm-crypt could be use now, and the flaw corrected in "
"the\n"
"kernel. It uses a definitly different process which may be explain in an "
"other\n"
"LFS hint.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:85
msgid ""
"So there is loop-AES. It is stable and modular and needs few modifications "
"to the base system. It consists of patches to apply to the kernel (2.4 and "
"2.6) and some utilities. Using multi-key with loop-AES avoids the flaw of "
"cryptoloop and dm-crypt. It uses the AES algorithm which is known to be one "
"of the strongest available. Moreover, there is already an LFS hint for "
"encrypting root partition using loop-AES [4]."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:88
msgid "You can find loop-AES here: http://sourceforge.net/projects/loop-aes/"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:93
msgid ""
"[1] http://lwn.net/Articles/67216/ [2] http://kerneltrap.org/node/2433 [3] "
"http://mareichelt.de/pub/texts.cryptoloop.php [4] "
"http://linuxfromscratch.org/~devine/erfs-howto.html"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:95
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"III. Encrypting swap\n"
"---------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:96
#, no-wrap
msgid "-----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:100
msgid ""
"It's a matter of applying 2 patches and changing a little the /etc/fstab "
"file.  The easiest way is to patch the svn version of the book like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:102 origin/eswap.txt:108
msgid "-- Optional --"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:106
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" wget ftp://ngc891.blogdns.net/pub/hlfs/hlfs-607-eswap-1.patch\n"
" cd HLFS\n"
" patch -Np1 -i ../hlfs-607-eswap-1.patch\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:110
msgid ""
"Unfortunatly, it can be out of date so you have choice to follow the other "
"way:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:114
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"1. First you need to apply the util-linux-2.12r-loop_AES-3.1b.patch to the\n"
"util-linux before building it during chapter 6. This patch enables the use "
"of \n"
"mount, umount, and swapon for encrypted devices.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:116
#, no-wrap
msgid " $ patch -Np1 -i ../util-linux-2.12r-loop_AES-3.1b.patch\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
#: origin/eswap.txt:118
msgid "You need to change the line about swap file in the /etc/fstab (chapter 7)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:121
msgid ""
"from:\t/dev/[yyy]\tswap\tswap\tpri=1\t0\t0 "
"to:\t/dev/[yyy]\tswap\tswap\tsw,loop=/dev/loop7,encryption=AES128,pri=1\t0\t0"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:125
msgid ""
"The swap will be mount using a loopback device with a multikeys AES "
"encryption.  It uses the last loop device so you will be able to use from "
"/dev/loop0 to /dev/loop6 for other purpose."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:129
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"3. \n"
"Finally, you must patch your kernel source before \"make menuconfig\" in\n"
"chapter 7:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:131
#, no-wrap
msgid " patch -Np1 -i ../linux-2.6.14.3-loop_AES-3.1b.patch\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/eswap.txt:135
msgid ""
"Then, during \"make menuconfig\", you MUST select loop-AES under loop item "
"of the block sub-section or your swap partition may not be available. You "
"should enable BLK_DEV_LOOP_AES and BLK_DEV_LOOP_KEYSCRUB."
msgstr ""

